---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="About — Fengze Jiang" description="A bit more about who I am and what I'm looking for.">
  <div class="about">
    <h1>About Me</h1>

    <section class="section">
      <p>
        I'm Fengze, an ML engineer based in <!-- your city -->. I build systems that put
        language models to practical use — the retrieval pipelines, evaluation frameworks, and
        inference infrastructure that make the difference between a cool demo and something
        that actually works in production.
      </p>
      <p>
        My background is in software engineering, and I came to ML through a genuine interest
        in what these models can and can't do rather than a straight academic path. That means
        I think about deployment and reliability as much as model quality, and I tend to reach
        for simple solutions before complex ones.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>How I got here</h2>
      <p>
        I started as a backend engineer, spending a few years building data pipelines and APIs.
        The shift toward ML was gradual — first adding model inference to existing services,
        then building the tooling around it (monitoring, evaluation, feature stores), and
        eventually focusing on LLM systems full-time when it became clear that was where
        the hardest and most interesting problems were.
      </p>
      <p>
        <!-- Add your own story here — why you switched, what you built along the way,
             a project that changed how you think, etc. -->
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>What I'm looking for</h2>
      <p>
        I'm most effective on small, high-trust teams where engineers own problems end-to-end —
        from defining what to measure to shipping the thing that improves the metric. I like
        working close to the product, not just the infrastructure.
      </p>
      <p>
        The problems I find most interesting right now: making LLM outputs reliably evaluable,
        building systems that degrade gracefully when the model is wrong, and the practical
        engineering of retrieval at scale.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Outside work</h2>
      <p>
        I build games on weekends — mostly small Unity projects where I can implement
        algorithms I find interesting (procedural generation, pathfinding, behaviour trees)
        without the pressure of a production codebase. A few of them are playable in the
        <a href="/projects">projects section</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
        I also write here occasionally, mostly as a way to force myself to actually understand
        things I've been treating as black boxes.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section contact-section">
      <h2>Get in touch</h2>
      <p>
        Best way to reach me is email:
        <a href="mailto:jiangfz1997@gmail.com">jiangfz1997@gmail.com</a>.
        I'm also on <a href="https://github.com/jiangfz1997" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>
        and <a href="https://linkedin.com/in/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">LinkedIn</a>.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>
</Base>

<style>
  .about {
    max-width: 640px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 2rem 0;
  }

  h1 {
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }

  .section {
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
  }

  .section h2 {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--color-text);
  }

  .section p {
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    line-height: 1.75;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .section p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .contact-section p {
    color: var(--color-text);
  }
</style>
